04674nam a22006735i 9780271022697DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710226977 a10.1515/97802710226972doi  a(DE-B1597)583871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX1530b.B97 2005eb 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a322/.1/09442221 aByrnes, Joseph F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatholic and French Forever :bReligious and National Identity in Modern France /cJoseph F. Byrnes. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Divorce -- tIntroduction -- t1 Between Church and Nation -- t2 National Ideals and Their Failure -- t3 Religious and Secular Extremes at the Beginning of the Nineteenth Century -- tPart II. Defense -- tIntroduction -- t4 Piety Against Politics -- t5 Local Languages for the Defense of Religion -- tPart III. Détente -- tIntroduction -- t6 The Limits of Personal Reconciliation -- t7 Reconciliation of Cultures in the Third Republic -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: The “Nation” Conundrum -- tNotes -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is often said that there are two Frances—Catholic and secular. This notion dates back to the 1790s, when the revolutionary government sought to divorce Catholic Christianity from national life. While Napoleon formally reconciled his regime to France’s millions of Catholics, church-state relations have remained a source of conflict and debate throughout the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. In Catholic and French Forever Joseph Byrnes recounts the fights and reconciliations between French citizens who found Catholicism integral to their traditional French identity and those who found the continued presence of Catholicism an obstacle to both happiness and progress. He does so through stories of priests, legislators, intellectuals, and pilgrims whose experiences manifest the problem of being both Catholic and French in modern France. Byrnes finds that loyalties to the French nation and Catholicism became so incompatible in the revolutionary era that Catholic believers responded defensively across the nineteenth century, politicizing both religious pilgrimage and the languages of religious instruction. He shows that a détente emerged in the first decades of the twentieth century with the respect given to priests in arms during World War I and to the work of religious art historian Émile Mâle. This détente has lasted, precariously and with interruption, up to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChurch and statexCatholic ChurchxHistoryy19th century. 0aChurch and statexCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20th century. 0aChurch and statezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aChurch and statezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271022697zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271022697423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271022697/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPD